00:11:29.400 --> 00:11:34.919
talk about Plumber API. And at the end, we will talk about the native application. So

00:11:34.919 --> 00:11:39.159
let's start with scaling. In order to scale your Shiny application and to be successful

00:11:39.159 --> 00:11:44.799
in production, you need to follow very simple rules to have a good application architecture.

00:11:44.799 --> 00:11:49.520
First of all, try to extract the computations from the server. As you know, R is single

00:11:49.520 --> 00:11:54.960
threaded. And you need to make sure that you don't put too much load on the server while

00:11:54.960 --> 00:11:59.559
it is running. So you can use the database. You can run the ETLs. You can extract the

00:11:59.559 --> 00:12:05.960
processes away from the app and just trigger those processes and go back to the main thread.

00:12:05.960 --> 00:12:11.200
Also, you should make Shiny layer thin. Shiny is a great middleware that connects frontend

00:12:11.200 --> 00:12:17.039
with the backend. And this is great for communication. Then you should leverage frontend. JavaScript

00:12:17.039 --> 00:12:22.400
is a perfect tool. It actually allows you to create great interactions. And sometimes

00:12:22.400 --> 00:12:27.520
you don't need even to communicate with the backend to do some amazing actions on the

00:12:27.520 --> 00:12:33.239
frontend. So when you have the right architecture, there is a time to deploy your application

00:12:33.239 --> 00:12:38.479
to RStudio Connect. RStudio Connect is great not only because you get the authentication,

00:12:38.479 --> 00:12:44.599
but actually it automatically scales all the processes behind. So it is capable to serve

00:12:44.599 --> 00:12:50.159
as many users as it is possible on one single machine. But of course, sometimes it is not

00:12:50.159 --> 00:12:54.479
enough to have just one machine serving all your users, especially if you have an application

00:12:54.479 --> 00:13:00.200
that has 1,000 users. And you have seen last year that Sean was talking about even scaling

00:13:00.200 --> 00:13:05.520
to 10,000 users. So this is not possible on a very small one machine.

00:13:05.520 --> 00:13:10.640
So in order to do that, I suggest to have a very good preparation first. We often use

00:13:10.640 --> 00:13:15.520
Ansible that allows you to actually automate the process of installing all the software

00:13:15.520 --> 00:13:20.200
and deploying it on RStudio Connect. So when you have a bare metal or you just spin up

00:13:20.200 --> 00:13:26.440
an instance in the cloud, you can just run one single command and deploy everything,

00:13:26.440 --> 00:13:31.799
provision, install all of the requirements, and it just works. So when you have that,

00:13:31.799 --> 00:13:36.440
you can create an architecture that will allow you to serve a lot of users. You can scale

