So let's look at Plumber API. Probably most of you already know Plumber, so I'm just going

00:14:19.000 --> 00:14:24.679
to briefly tell you how it works. Plumber is a package from RStudio, and it allows you

00:14:24.679 --> 00:14:31.840
to simply change a function into an HTTP API. So when you look at the example here, you

00:14:31.840 --> 00:14:37.840
have a function that has arguments A and B, and it returns just a sum of those two.

00:14:37.840 --> 00:14:43.559
By adding simple annotations in the comments, you are able to create an endpoint that when

00:14:43.559 --> 00:14:49.280
the whole project is deployed, you can just call, for example, CURL and pass the data

00:14:49.280 --> 00:14:56.239
as a post to get the result. So now when we have the whole infrastructure and we have

00:14:56.239 --> 00:15:01.520
the Plumber API endpoints that serve the data to you, this is probably the hardest part.

00:15:01.520 --> 00:15:07.840
So the native application. The problem is that we are not able to build a whole native

00:15:07.840 --> 00:15:14.719
application with Shiny, but as you are advanced Shiny developers, you already probably have

00:15:14.719 --> 00:15:19.280
worked with JavaScript as well. So the good news is that you can leverage your JavaScript

